Dataset Description

The dataset contains information about bookings made at a resort hotel. The data includes information about the booking, the customer, and the stay. The data can be downloaded here (hotels_tidy.csv).

Below you can find a glimpse of the dataset.

Columns

Below, you can find a description of the actual columns used in this dataset.

  • LeadTime: Number of days between booking and arrival
  • ArrivalDateYear: Year of the booking arrival (2015, 2016, or 2017)
  • ArrivalDateMonth: Month of arrival (January to December)
  • ArrivalDateDayOfMonth: Day of the month of the arrival date
  • StaysInWeekendNights: Number of weekend nights (Saturday or Sunday) the guest stayed or booked
  • StaysInWeekNights: Number of weeknights (Monday to Friday) the guest stayed or booked
  • MarketSegment: Segment of the market that generated the booking (e.g., Direct, Corporate, Travel Agent)
  • DistributionChannel: Channel through which the booking was made (e.g., Direct, Travel Agent, Online)
  • IsRepeatedGuest: Indicates whether the guest has booked before (1 = Yes, 0 = No)
  • PreviousCancellations: Number of previous cancellations by the customer
  • PreviousBookingsNotCanceled: Number of previous bookings that were not canceled by the customer
  • ReservedRoomType: Code for the type of room reserved by the customer. Code is presented instead of designation for anonymity reasons
  • BookingChanges: Number of modifications made to the booking
  • Agent: ID of the travel agency that made the booking (if applicable)
  • Company: ID of the company paying for the booking (if applicable)
  • DaysInWaitingList: Number of days the booking was on a waiting list before confirmation
  • CustomerType: Classification of the customer (e.g., Transient, Contract, Group)
  • ADR: Average Daily Rate, calculated as total revenue divided by the number of nights
  • RequiredCarParkingSpaces: Number of parking spaces required by the guest
  • TotalOfSpecialRequests: Number of special requests made (e.g., high floor, twin bed)

Homework Rules

You are required to create a single, tidy dataset.

  • You will work in groups of 3-5 people.
  • You should explore the data (descriptive statistics, plots, etc.) to identify any problematic aspects.
  • You need to submit the following files:
    • A Python notebook (tidy_homework_group_name.ipynb) that uses the hotels_tidy.csv file as input, performs the explorative analysis, and produces a clean dataset.
    • A comma-separated file containing the tidy dataset (tidy_dataset_group_name.csv) generated by the aforementioned Python notebook.
Tip

  • You can and should explore the data to identify potential issues, but you should not impute or modify the information contained in the dataset. This kind of manipulation would be considered pre-processing, which might be needed in the second project but is not the goal of this homework.

  • The creation of new columns is allowed as long as it aims to simplify the data structure. For example, you can create a single column with the âdate and timeâ by combining existing columns, but you should not compute and save, for instance, the logarithm of the average daily rate.

  • Please keep the Python notebook concise and to the point. There is no strict page limit (as Jupyter Notebooks do not have pages), nor is there a maximum number of plots or tables you can display. However, understanding which parts of the exploratory analysis are relevant is a key skill in data science.
